footnotes = \n| website = http://www.ocpgroup.ma/en\n}}\n\nThe '''OCP Group''' (OCP S.A.) (formerly Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates) is a Moroccan based [[phosphate]] rock miner, [[phosphoric acid]] manufacturer and [[Fertilizer|phosphate fertilizer]] producer. <ref>{{cite journal |title=Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates (Morocco)|url=http://www.solpart-project.eu/about-us/partners/ocp/ |journal=Solpart Project|date = 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=OCP Group: Major Business Opportunities|url=http://www.syitc.com/events/ocp-group-major-business-opportunities/|journal=SYITC|date=November 1, 2016|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106012533/http://www.syitc.com/events/ocp-group-major-business-opportunities/|archive-date=January 6, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Founded in 1920, the company has grown into one of the world\u2019s largest producers of phosphate and phosphate-based products.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Company Overview of OCP S.A.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=5476844|journal=Bloomberg|date = 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Group Client|url=http://www.architectepartners.com/ocp-group-client-6-Part-191.html|journal=Architecte Partners|date = 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Maroc |url=https://www.blacktogreen.com/portfolio_item/ocp-maroc/|journal=Black to Green|date = 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/sites/default/files/2019-05/RA%20OCP%202017%20VUK.pdf|title=2017 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOCP has access to more than 70% of the world\u2019s phosphate rock reserves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usgs.gov/centers/nmic/phosphate-rock-statistics-and-information|title=Phosphate Rock Statistics and Information|website=www.usgs.gov|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Initially a [[mining]] company, OCP has diversified in 1965 to become a phosphate processor, making it one of the world\u2019s leading fertilizer manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/en|title=Home {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The company holds a 31% market share of the world phosphate product market.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe group employs nearly 23,000 people in Morocco and a number of international subsidiaries. In 2018, its revenues amounted to US$5.884 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/en/who-we-are/ocp-glance|title=OCP at a glance {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Origins ===\nThe OCP Group was founded in [[Morocco]] in 1920 as the Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates following Royal Decree. Mining production began in 1921, when it began extracting phosphate rockat its first mine in Khouribga. Transportation of the phosphate to the port of [[Casablanca]] also started in 1921, allowing the first export of phosphate that year. Subsequently, OCP launched other mining sites in [[Youssoufia, Morocco|Youssoufia]] in 1931 and in [[Ben Guerir|Benguerir]] in 1976, and launched chemical production in Safi in 1965 and in [[Jorf Lasfar]] in 1984. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.monde-diplomatique.fr/1962/06/A/24781|title=L'Office ch\u00e9rifien des phosphates amorce une nouvelle phase d'expansion|date=1962-06-01|website=Le Monde diplomatique|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Ownership ===\nIn 2008, the OCP Group became a limited company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emis.com/php/company-profile/MA/Office_Chrifien_des_Phosphates_Group__OCP___%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%85%C3%98%C2%AC%C3%99%C2%85%C3%98%C2%B9_%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%99%C2%84%C3%98%C2%B4%C3%98%C2%B1%C3%99%C2%8A%C3%99%C2%81_%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%81%C3%99%C2%88%C3%98%C2%B3%C3%99%C2%81%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%98%C2%B7__en_3853612.html|title=Office Chrifien des Phosphates Group (OCP) Company Profile - Morocco {{!}} Financials & Key Executives {{!}} EMIS|website=www.emis.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.le360.ma/economie/ocp-group-reduit-sa-participation-dans-la-bcp-29317|title=OCP Group r\u00e9duit sa participation dans la BCP|website=fr.le360.ma|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Currently 95% of the OCP Group is owned by the Moroccan state and 5% by [[Banque Populaire du Maroc|Banque Centrale Populaire]] investment funds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/afrique/maroc-le-nouvel-age-d-or-des-phosphates_1072371.html|title=Maroc: le nouvel \u00e2ge d'or des phosphates|date=2012-01-17|website=LExpress.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.le360.ma/economie/ocp-group-reduit-sa-participation-dans-la-bcp-29317|title=OCP Group r\u00e9duit sa participation dans la BCP|website=fr.le360.ma|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate Timeline ===\n\n* '''1920''' Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates founded\n* '''1921''' Launch of mining production in Khouribga\n* '''1931''' Launch of mining production in Youssoufia\n* '''1965''' Launch of chemical production in Safi\n* '''1976''' Acquisition of 65% of Phosboucraa \n* '''1980''' Launch of mining production at Benguerir site\n* '''1984''' Launch of chemical production at Jorf Lasfar\n* '''1996''' Construction of purified phosphoric acid plant launched in Jorf Lasfar\n* '''2002''' OCP becomes sole owner of Phosboucraa\n* '''2006''' Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates becomes OCP \n* '''2008''' Transformation of Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates into a Corporation (OCP S.A)\n* '''2011''' Joint Venture with [[Jacobs Engineering Group|Jacobs Engineering]]\n* '''2013''' Joint Venture with [[DuPont|DuPont de Nemours]]\n* '''2014''' Launch of the Slurry Pipeline between Khouribga and Jorf Lasfar\n* '''2016''' Creation of OCP Africa\n* '''2018''' Inauguration of Mohammed VI Polytechnic University and Joint Venture with [[IBM]]\n\nIn 2007, the OCP Group set itself a target to triple its production of fertilizers by 2020.\n\nThe OCP Group plays an important economic and social role in Morocco. The value of phosphates and their derivatives represented nearly a quarter of the [[Economy of Morocco|country's exports]] and approximately 3.5% of the [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2010|title=Pr\u00e9sentation d'OCP|url=http://www.worldpolicyconference.com/presse.php?lien=sponsorpresse&&menu=2&&lang=fr&&edition=2010|journal=Site de la World Policy Conference|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130630162832/http://www.worldpolicyconference.com/presse.php?lien=sponsorpresse&&menu=2&&lang=fr&&edition=2010|archive-date=June 30, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=November 14, 2016|title=L'OCP: Le g\u00e9ant des phosphates made in Morocco|url=http://www.agrimaroc.ma/l-ocp-l-office-cherifien-des-phosphates/|journal=Agrimaroc}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[Fitch Ratings]] confirmed the rating of \"investment grade\" for the OCP Group.<ref>{{cite journal|date=December 15, 2016|title=Maroc : Fitch confirme l'Investment Grade \u00e0 OCP Group|url=http://www.lesafriques.com/actualite/maroc-fitch-confirme-l-investment-grade-a-ocp-group.html?Itemid=89?article=46364|journal=Les Afriques}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 15, 2016|title=Maroc : Fitch confirme l'Investment Grade \u00e0 OCP Group|url=https://www.afropages.fr/Les-Afriques/maroc-fitch-confirme-linvestment-grade-a-ocp-group|journal=Afropages|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113121650/https://www.afropages.fr/Les-Afriques/maroc-fitch-confirme-linvestment-grade-a-ocp-group|archive-date=January 13, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=April 3, 2014|title=Fitch Rates Morocco's OCP 'BBB-'; Proposed Notes 'BBB-(EXP)'|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFFit69584420140403|journal=Reuters Africa}}</ref>\n\nAfter approval from the AMMC ((Moroccan Authority of the Capital Market) Autorit\u00e9 Marocaine du March\u00e9 des Capitaux) on December 9, 2016, the OCP Group managed to reach 10.2&nbsp;billion [[Dirham|dirhams]] of bonds from the national community. This loan is the largest ever made in the Moroccan market.<ref>{{cite journal|date=December 23, 2016|title=Carton plein pour l'\u00e9mission obligataire d'OCP|url=http://telquel.ma/2016/12/23/banco-lemission-obligataire-docp_1528395|journal=Telquel}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 19, 2016|title=OCP cl\u00f4ture avec succ\u00e8s son \u00e9mission obligataire|url=http://www.leconomiste.com/flash-infos/ocp-cloture-avec-succes-son-emission-obligataire|journal=L'\u00e9conomiste}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=November 29, 2016|title=OCP : L'AMMC donne son feu vert \u00e0 un emprunt obligataire de 5 milliards de dirhams|url=https://www.yabiladi.com/articles/details/48810/l-ammc-donne-vert-emprunt-obligataire.html|journal=Yabiladi}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 14, 2014|title=OCP: \u00e9mission d'un emprunt obligataire de 5 milliards de dirhams|url=http://www.h24info.ma/economie/entreprises/ocp-emission-dun-emprunt-obligataire-de-5-milliards-de-dirhams/49090|journal=24h Info|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228082024/http://www.h24info.ma/economie/entreprises/ocp-emission-dun-emprunt-obligataire-de-5-milliards-de-dirhams/49090|archive-date=February 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 1, 2016|title=OCP finance l'expansion de son appareil productif et apure ses dettes|url=http://www.jeuneafrique.com/378734/economie/ocp-finance-lexpansion-de-appareil-productif-apure-dettes/|journal=Jeune Afrique}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the OCP Group created a new subsidiary named OCP Africa, which is responsible for leading the development of the group in the African fertilizer market through a network of subsidiaries in 12 African countries.\n\nIn the same year, OCP adopted a new internal culture, called \u2018Le Movement\u2019, aimed at re-focusing the group even more strongly on innovation.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gasteyger|first=Curt|title=Chapitre VII. Les armements dans le tiers-monde|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4000/books.iheid.4492|work=Les d\u00e9fis de la paix|pages=99\u2013109|publisher=Graduate Institute Publications|isbn=978-2-13-039917-9|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== Operations ==\n\n=== Mines and Key Sites ===\n\n==== Khouribga ====\nOCP\u2019s first mine opened in Khouribga in 1921. The [[Khouribga]] area has the richest phosphate deposits in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1163/_afco_asc_3086|title=Festival du Cin\u00e9ma Africain de Khouribga (Khouribga, Morocco)|website=African Studies Companion Online|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>In 2014, a [[slurry pipeline]] between Khouribga and [[Jorf Lasfar]] was launched, which transports phosphate from the mines to the processing facility safely and efficiently. The pipeline, one world\u2019s longest [[Pipeline transport|gravity powered pipelines]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rusconi|first=Julian|last2=Lakhouaja|first2=Anis|last3=Kopuz|first3=Mustafa|date=2016-01-01|title=The Design and Engineering of the 187 km Khouribga to Jorf Lasfar Phosphate Slurry Pipeline|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1877705816004367|journal=Procedia Engineering|series=SYMPHOS 2015 - 3rd International Symposium on Innovation and Technology in the Phosphate Industry|language=en|volume=138|pages=142\u2013150|doi=10.1016/j.proeng.2016.02.072|issn=1877-7058}}</ref> saves more than 3Mm3 of water per year, as well as a significant amount of energy.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/sites/default/files/2019-07/Sustainability%20report%202018%20OCP.pdf|title=2019 Sustainability Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>The site employs more people than any other OCP mine, which is more than 6,100 people.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2016, the mine produced 18.9[[Metric ton|MT]] of Phosphate Rock, or 70% of the total group output.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/sites/default/files/2018-11/RA%20OCP%202016%20VUK.pdf|title=2016 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the OCP Group started a new mining project in Sidi Chennane in the Khouribga area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1787/873102715006|title=Paraguay\u00a0: Croissance de la p\u00e9n\u00e9tration du mobile|website=dx.doi.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>The construction of the purified phosphoric acid plant was launched in Jorf Lasfar in 1996 and started production in 1998.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=El Falaki|first=K.|last2=Lhadi|first2=E. K.|date=2001|title=Contribution \u00e0 l\u2019\u00e9tude d\u2019impact de l\u2019\u00e9pandage d\u2019eaux us\u00e9es brutes sur l\u2019environnement dans la r\u00e9gion de Zemamra (province d\u2019El Jadida, Maroc)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4267/dechets-sciences-techniques.1399|journal=D\u00e9chets, sciences et techniques|issue=24|doi=10.4267/dechets-sciences-techniques.1399|issn=2268-7289}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the OCP Group inaugurated the slurry pipeline linking Khouribga to Jorf Lasfar, a technological advancement in the transportation of phosphates.<ref>{{Citation|last=de Blas|first=Ceferino|title=A cidade de Cunqueiro. Tres directores, tres d\u00e9cadas, un xornal|date=2015|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.17075/mucnoc.2014.063|work=Mil e un Cunqueiros. Novas olladas para un centenario|publisher=Consello da Cultura Galega|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, a fertilizer production plant dedicated entirely to Africa was inaugurated at Jorf Lasfar, the African Fertilizer Complex. Connected to the slurry pipeline, JFC 4 will be fully integrated and have its own thermoelectric plant. These plants not only make Jorf Lasfar completely energy self-sufficient, they also create an energy surplus that fuels the complex\u2019s sea water [[desalination]] station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/index.php/en/our-strategy/our-industrial-and-commercial-strategy/jorf-lasfar-largest-fertilizer-complex-world|title=Jorf Lasfar, the largest fertilizer complex in the world {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==== Gantour (Benguerir and Youssoufia) ====\nGantour is made up of two mining facilities, [[Ben Guerir|Benguerir]] and [[Youssoufia, Morocco|Youssoufia]] and holds the second largest amount of Morocco\u2019s phosphate reserves, 37% of the total.\n\nThe mine in Benguerir opened in 1980. It is situated 70km north of [[Marrakesh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mining-technology.com/projects/benguearir/|title=Moroccan Office Cherifi\u00e9n des Phosphates phosphate rock mine|website=Mining Technology {{!}} Mining News and Views Updated Daily|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 the mines\u2019 produced 6.3MT of [[Phosphorite|Phosphate Rock]], representing 23% of the group\u2019s total output.<ref name=\":2\" /> Since 2017 the mine has been one of Mohammed VI Polytechnic University\u2019s testing sites that is open to the scientific community and allows researchers from partner universities to test full-scale solutions in key areas. Called the \u201cAdvanced Mining Technology Platform,\u201d this pilot mine has many purposes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/en/our-strategy/our-industrial-and-commercial-strategy/benguerir-mine|title=The Benguerir Mine {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nRock from Benguerir is transported by rail to [[Safi, Morocco|Safi]] by [[ONCF]], the national railway company of Morocco. \n\nThe Group's activities are organised into an integrated model covering all operations of the value chain from the extraction of phosphates to the production and marketing of various products including fertilizers and phosphoric acid.<ref name=\"lexpress\">{{cite journal |title=Maroc: le nouvel \u00e2ge d'or des phosphates|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/afrique/maroc-le-nouvel-age-d-or-des-phosphates_1072371.html |journal=Jeune Afrique|date = January 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe mine in Youssoufia is the second most important mine to the Moroccan economy after the Khouribga mine. It is also the third biggest producer world wide of phosphate.<ref>{{Citation|title=Youssoufia (Maroc)|date=2020-02-08|url=https://fr.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Youssoufia_(Maroc)&oldid=167208539|work=Wikip\u00e9dia|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nSince 1998, OCP has also operated the [[Bouchane]] mine, which is situated 40km from Youssoufia. The phosphate from this mine is also processed at Youssoufia. \n\n==== Jorf Lasfar ====\nThe Jorf Lasfar processing platform is the largest fertilizer complex in the world. The first phase of the site opened in 1984 and has been expanded multiple times since. Products are made using phosphate rock mined in Khouribga. The site produced 4.63Mt of fertilizer in 2016, including, 1.86Mt [[Phosphoric acid]], 1.91Mt [[Ammonium dihydrogen phosphate|MAP]], and 1.14Mt [[Diammonium phosphate|DAP]]. Over 30 different of fertilizer were produced to suit various [[Soil type|soil types]]. The complex is made up of several units including the newest, the Africa fertilizer complex and JFC II.<ref name=\":2\" /> The site is the world\u2019s largest exporter of fertilizer. The site has a [[desalination plant]] with a capacity of 25[[\u33a3|Mm3]] per year \u2013 since its construction this has significantly reduced the amount of water consumed by the plant from local sources.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Safi ====\nThe first OCP chemical site, the Safi complex started its activities in 1965 to process the phosphate rock from Benguerir. In addition to ferilizser and phosphoric acid production unites the site has a phosphate washing unit and a sulfuric acid plant.\n\nIn 2016 the site produced 1.5Mt of phosphoric acid and 832.6Kt of [[Monocalcium phosphate|TSP fertilizer.]] These figures represented the highest production figures in the site\u2019s history.<ref name=\":2\" />The site produces fertilizer for both the domestic and international markets. \n\n==== Phosboucraa (Subsidiary) ====\nIn 1976, OCP acquired 65% of Phosboucraa mine ([[Bou Craa|Boucra\u00e2]]-[[Laayoune]]), and became the sole owner in 2002. \n\nOperations at the mine originally began in 1972; its activity includesmining, processing and marketing phosphate rock. Boucraa mine represents approximately 2% of the Morocco\u2019s total phosphate reserves, 4.6% of OCP Group\u2019s total revenue and around 8% of the total rock extracted.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://phosboucraa.ma/company/about-phosboucraa|title=PHOSBOUCRAA {{!}} About Phosboucraa|website=phosboucraa.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\n100% of profits made in the region are reinvested in the local community through the Phosboucraa Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/sites/default/files/2019-11/OCP_NIYA_communityReport.pdf|title=NIYA: Community Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Phosboucraa Foundation has so far helped more the 50,000 people through its various programs in education, health, and entrepreneurship.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nPhosboucraa\u2019s activities are located in 3 different places:\n\n* [[Mining]] activities are located 140 km away by road from La\u00e2youne, thus far from any possible shipping area\n* The processing plant and the wharf are located at [[Atlantic Ocean|La\u00e2youne beach]], 20 km away from the city. A 102 km long [[conveyor belt]] is used for transporting phosphates from the Mine to La\u00e2youne beach\n* Headquarters are located in La\u00e2youne city\n\nTo help develop the value chain at this site OCP is investing $2.2billion to build a phosphate processing plant, producing fertilizer and phosphoric acid. The scheme is expected to create more than 5,000 job in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.phosboucraa.ma/company/key-figures/industrial-investments|title=PHOSBOUCRAA {{!}} Industrial Investments|website=www.phosboucraa.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nThe project will continue the groups policy of hiring local workers, which now make up 76% of the workforce, up from just 4% in 1976. This has been achieved through outreach and training programs, upskilling locals to take on these roles. These schemes have also led to hundreds of workers being trained to do skilled work at the groups site in the North.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.phosboucraa.ma/company/|title=Company|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== OCP Globally ==\n\n==== OCP Africa ====\nIn February 2016, the OCP Group created a new subsidiary named OCP Africa, which is responsible for leading the development of the group on the African fertilizer market through a network of subsidiaries in 5 African countries. The subsidiary was granted the status of Casablanca Finance City (CFC) for investors on the African continent to benefit from an attractive package of tax incentives and other opportunities.<ref name=Agefi>{{cite journal |title=Trading \u00e0 Gen\u00e8ve pour le g\u00e9ant marocain des phosphates|url=http://www.agefi.com/quotidien-agefi/suisse/detail/edition/2016-06-03/article/ocp-loffice-cherifien-des-phosphates-vient-douvrir-une-entite-de-negoce-en-suisse-sous-le-nom-de-saftco--428186.html|journal=Agefi|date = June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Group launches new subsidiary|url=http://www.africanfarming.net/crops/agriculture/ocp-group-launches-new-subsidiary|journal=African Farming|date = March 30, 2016}}</ref> The OCP projects in Africa cover the entire value chain, including the local construction of fertilizer plants, the development of logistics and distribution capabilities, as well as investment in research for the development of formulas adapted for the soils and crops (mapping the African soil fertility and respective fertilizer needs). The African Development Bank (ADB) has pledged to support the various initiatives of the OCP Group in favour of the African continent.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Maroc : Akinwumi Adesina chez Terrab, PDG OCP Group|url=http://www.lesafriques.com/actualite/maroc-akinwumi-adesina-chez-terrab-pdg-ocp-group.html?Itemid=89|journal=Les Afriques|date = July 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Le groupe OCP lance sa filiale OCP Africa pour renforcer le d\u00e9veloppement agricole de l'Afrique |url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/02/25/ocp-africa-nouvelle-filiale-developpement-agricole_n_9318388.html |journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = February 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=C\u00f4te d'Ivoire/International/ Le PDG du Groupe OCP re\u00e7oit le Pr\u00e9sident du Groupe de la BAD (Communiqu\u00e9)|url=http://news.abidjan.net/h/595029.html|journal=Abidjan.net|date = July 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=A la COP 22, l'accord sur l'agriculture en friche|url=http://www.liberation.fr/planete/2016/11/17/a-la-cop-22-l-accord-sur-l-agriculture-en-friche_1529165|journal=Lib\u00e9ration|date = November 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe OCP Group plans to open 14 new branches in Sub-Saharan Africa to make a promising entry into the African market. The main countries targeted by this operation are: [[C\u00f4te d\u2019Ivoire]], [[Senegal]], [[the Democratic Republic of Congo]], [[Benin]], [[Cameroon]], Nigeria, [[Tanzania]], [[Angola]], [[Zambia]], [[Zimbabwe]], [[Mozambique]], [[Kenya]], [[Ghana]], and [[Ethiopia]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Maroc : le groupe OCP pr\u00e9voit 14 nouvelles filiales en Afrique subsaharienne|url=http://www.financialafrik.com/2016/08/05/maroc-le-groupe-ocp-prevoit-14-nouvelles-filiales-en-afrique-subsaharienne/|journal=Financial Afrik|date = August 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Nigeria]] ====\nIn 2016, the Morrocan head of state and King Mohammed VI presided over the ceremony marking the launch of a strategic partnership for the development of the fertilizer industry in Nigeria. In particular, this partnership includes an agreement between the OCP Group and Dangote Industries Limited for creating a platform for fertilizer production in Nigeria. Similarly, an agreement for developing the fertilizer market was signed between the OCP Group and the association of fertilizer producers and suppliers in Nigeria.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Maroc/Nig\u00e9ria : Plusieurs accords sign\u00e9s aujourd'hui, les d\u00e9tails|url=http://www.infomediaire.net/news/maroc/marocnigeria-plusieurs-accords-signes-aujourdhui-les-details|journal=Infom\u00e9diaire|date=December 2, 2016}}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi et le Chef de l'Etat nig\u00e9rian pr\u00e9sident la c\u00e9r\u00e9monie de lancement d'un partenariat strat\u00e9gique pour le d\u00e9veloppement de l'industrie des engrais au Nig\u00e9ria|url=http://www.mapexpress.ma/actualite/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-et-le-chef-de-letat-nigerian-president-la-ceremonie-de-lancement-dun-partenariat-strategique-pour-le-developpement-de-lindustrie-des-engrais-au-nigeria/|journal=MA Express|date = December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Accord OCP-Dangote: quand le premier producteur mondial d\u2019engrais tend la main \u00e0 l\u2019homme le plus riche d\u2019Afrique|url=http://www.financialafrik.com/2016/12/03/accord-ocp-dangote-quand-le-premier-producteur-mondial-dengrais-tend-la-main-a-lhomme-le-plus-riche-dafrique/#.WIHjALbhDUI|journal=Financial Afrik|date = December 3, 2016}}</ref> Likewise, a pipeline project linking Nigeria to Morocco, passing through several countries in West Africa, is about to take shape.<ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi pr\u00e9side \u00e0 Casablanca une s\u00e9ance de travail consacr\u00e9e au projet de gazoduc, reliant le Nig\u00e9ria au Maroc \u00e0 travers plusieurs pays d'Afrique de l'ouest |url=http://www.mapexpress.ma/actualite/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-preside-a-casablanca-une-seance-de-travail-consacree-au-projet-de-gazoduc-reliant-le-nigeria-au-maroc-a-travers-plusieurs-pays-dafrique-de-louest-cabinet-royal/|journal=Agence de presse marocaine|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi pr\u00e9side \u00e0 Casablanca une s\u00e9ance de travail consacr\u00e9e au projet de gazoduc, reliant le Nig\u00e9ria au Maroc \u00e0 travers plusieurs pays d'Afrique de l'ouest|url=http://www.maroc.ma/fr/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-preside-casablanca-une-seance-de-travail-consacree-au-projet-de-gazoduc|journal=Maroc|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Alerte : Le Maroc passe \u00e0 l'acte pour le gazoduc g\u00e9ant, r\u00e9union royale \u00e0 Casablanca|url=http://www.infomediaire.net/news/maroc/alerte-le-maroc-passe-lacte-pour-le-gazoduc-geant-reunion-royale-casablanca|journal=InfoM\u00e9diaire|date=December 13, 2016|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217064419/http://www.infomediaire.net/news/maroc/alerte-le-maroc-passe-lacte-pour-le-gazoduc-geant-reunion-royale-casablanca|archive-date=February 17, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Gazoduc nig\u00e9ria-maroc: le roi pr\u00e9side une s\u00e9ance de travail sur la faisabilit\u00e9 et le financement |url=http://www.bladi.info/threads/gazoduc-nigeria-maroc-roi-preside.445289/|journal=Bladi|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Mohammed VI \u00e9tudie la faisabilit\u00e9 technique et le financement du projet de gazoduc|url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/12/13/mohammed-vi-etudie-faisabilite-technique-financement-projet-gazoduc_n_13606152.html?ir=Maroc|journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Rwanda]] ====\nIn October 2016, during the visit of King Mohammed VI, the Ministry of Agriculture and Animal Resources signed an agreement with the OCP Group for the construction of a fertilizer plant in the country to facilitate access to these local farmers.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Rwanda's move towards green agric gains momentum|url=http://www.newtimes.co.rw/section/article/2016-12-11/206163/|journal=The New Times|date = December 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Saftco ===\nOn May 25, 2016, the OCP Group opened a commodity trading entity in Switzerland that includes phosphate, fertilizers and chemical products.<ref name=Agefi/><ref>{{cite journal |title=L'Office ch\u00e9rifien des phosphates ouvre une filiale \u00e0 Gen\u00e8ve|url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/06/03/ocp-geneve-maroc_n_10274720.html|journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = June 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Financial information ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n |+ Figures 2009 \u2013 2018\n |-\n |\n !scope=\"col\"| 2009\n !scope=\"col\"| 2010\n !scope=\"col\"| 2011\n !scope=\"col\"| 2012\n !scope=\"col\"| 2013\n !scope=\"col\"| 2014\n !scope=\"col\"| 2015\n !scope=\"col\"| 2016\n !scope=\"col\"| 2017\n !scope=\"col\"| 2018 \n |-\n !scope=\"row\"| Turnover (billions of MAD)\n | 25.3\n | 43.5\n | 56.4\n | 59.4\n |46.2\n |41.4\n |47.7\n |42.5\n |48.5\n |55.9\n|-\n ! scope=\"row\" | Profit (billions of MAD)\n | 1.3\n | 8.8\n | 16.3\n | 14.1\n |7.1\n |7.6\n |\n |\n |\n |5.4\n |\n |}\n\n== Executives (2016) ==\n\n=== Top Management ===\n* Chairman & CEO: [[Mostafa Terrab]]\n\n=== Senior Management ===\n* Executive vice president strategy & corporate development : Marouane Ameziane\n* Executive vice president sales & marketing : Mohamed Belhoussain\n* Executive vice president legal & corporate affairs : Otmane Bennani-Smires\n* Executive vice president human capital: Faris Derrij\n* Executive vice president industrial development: Abdelaziz El Mallah\n* Executive vice president industrial operations: Iliass Elfali\n* Executive vice president performance Management : Nada Elmajdoub\n* Executive vice president chief financial officer: Ghislane Guedira\n* Executive vice president digital office : Mohamed Laklalech\n* Executive vice president Africa : Karim Lotfi Senhadji\n\n== 2020 coronavirus crisis response ==\nOCP Group contributed $310 million the Moroccan emergency fund, created by [[Mohammed VI of Morocco|King Mohammed IV]] on 15 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2020/03/296549/moroccan-government-members-donate-salaries-to-covid-19-fund/|title=Moroccan Government Members Donate Salaries to COVID-19 Fund|last=Hekking|first=Morgan|date=2020-03-17|website=Morocco World News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-morocco-idUSKBN212173|title=Morocco to create $1 billion fund to counter coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-03-15|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ocpgroup.ma/en Official website of the OCP Group]\n* [http://www.ocpafrica.com/ Official website of OCP Africa]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Economy of Morocco]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Office Cherifien des Phosphates}}\n[[Category:1920 establishments in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Phosphate mining]]\n[[Category:Fertilizer companies of Morocco]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of Morocco]]\n[[Category:Mining companies of Morocco]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = OCP Group\n| logo = Ocp.jpg\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_padding = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| founded = 1920\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = [[Casablanca]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Morocco]]\n| key_people = [[Mostafa Terrab]] (Chairman)\n| industry = Phosphates, Chemicals\n| revenue = {{increase}} US$5.884 &nbsp;billion\n| revenue_year = 2018\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = \n| net_income = {{increase}} US$586.42&nbsp;million\n| net_income_year = 2018\n| aum = <!-- Only for financial-service companies -->\n| assets = \n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (when known) -->\n| equity = \n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (when known) -->\n| owner = [[Politics of Morocco|Government of Morocco]] (95%)\n| num_employees = about 20.000\n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (when known) -->\n| subsid = '''Mining & processing'''<br/><br/>Phosboucra\u00e2<br/>Prayon<br/>Euro Maroc Phosphore<br/>Jorf Fertilizer Company<br/>Indo Maroc Phosphore<br/>Pakistan Maroc Phosphore<br/>Zuari Maroc Phosphates Limited<br/>Paradeep Phosphates Limited<br/><br/>'''International & trading'''<br/><br/>OCP International<br/>OCP Fertilizantes<br/>OCP de Argentina<br/>OCP do Brazil<br/>Black Sea Fertilizer Trading Company<br/>OCP Africa<br/><br/>'''Engineering & Consulting'''<br/><br/>[[Jacobs Engineering S.A]]<br/>OCP Solutions<br/><br/>Teal Technology Services<br/><br/>Transportation Engineering and Management Consultants<br/>DuPont OCP Operations Consulting<br/><br/>'''Ecosystem Development'''<br/><br/>Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 d'Am\u00e9nagement et de D\u00e9veloppement Vert<br/>Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 d'Am\u00e9nagement et de D\u00e9veloppement de Mazagan<br/>OCP Innovation Fund for Agriculture<br/>Fondation OCP<br/>Fondation Phosboucra\u00e2\n| footnotes = \n| website = http://www.ocpgroup.ma/en\n}}\n\nThe '''OCP Group''' (OCP S.A.) (formerly Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates) is a Moroccan based [[phosphate]] rock miner, [[phosphoric acid]] manufacturer and [[Fertilizer|phosphate fertilizer]] producer. <ref>{{cite journal |title=Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates (Morocco)|url=http://www.solpart-project.eu/about-us/partners/ocp/ |journal=Solpart Project|date = 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=OCP Group: Major Business Opportunities|url=http://www.syitc.com/events/ocp-group-major-business-opportunities/|journal=SYITC|date=November 1, 2016|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106012533/http://www.syitc.com/events/ocp-group-major-business-opportunities/|archive-date=January 6, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Founded in 1920, the company has grown into one of the world\u2019s largest producers of phosphate and phosphate-based products.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Company Overview of OCP S.A.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=5476844|journal=Bloomberg|date = 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Group Client|url=http://www.architectepartners.com/ocp-group-client-6-Part-191.html|journal=Architecte Partners|date = 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Maroc |url=https://www.blacktogreen.com/portfolio_item/ocp-maroc/|journal=Black to Green|date = 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/sites/default/files/2019-05/RA%20OCP%202017%20VUK.pdf|title=2017 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOCP has access to more than 70% of the world\u2019s phosphate rock reserves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usgs.gov/centers/nmic/phosphate-rock-statistics-and-information|title=Phosphate Rock Statistics and Information|website=www.usgs.gov|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Initially a [[mining]] company, OCP has diversified in 1965 to become a phosphate processor, making it one of the world\u2019s leading fertilizer manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/en|title=Home {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The company holds a 31% market share of the world phosphate product market.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe group employs nearly 23,000 people in Morocco and a number of international subsidiaries. In 2018, its revenues amounted to US$5.884 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/en/who-we-are/ocp-glance|title=OCP at a glance {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Origins ===\nThe OCP Group was founded in [[Morocco]] in 1920 as the Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates following Royal Decree. Mining production began in 1921, when it began extracting phosphate rockat its first mine in Khouribga. Transportation of the phosphate to the port of [[Casablanca]] also started in 1921, allowing the first export of phosphate that year. Subsequently, OCP launched other mining sites in [[Youssoufia, Morocco|Youssoufia]] in 1931 and in [[Ben Guerir|Benguerir]] in 1976, and launched chemical production in Safi in 1965 and in [[Jorf Lasfar]] in 1984. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.monde-diplomatique.fr/1962/06/A/24781|title=L'Office ch\u00e9rifien des phosphates amorce une nouvelle phase d'expansion|date=1962-06-01|website=Le Monde diplomatique|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Ownership ===\nIn 2008, the OCP Group became a limited company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emis.com/php/company-profile/MA/Office_Chrifien_des_Phosphates_Group__OCP___%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%85%C3%98%C2%AC%C3%99%C2%85%C3%98%C2%B9_%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%99%C2%84%C3%98%C2%B4%C3%98%C2%B1%C3%99%C2%8A%C3%99%C2%81_%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%81%C3%99%C2%88%C3%98%C2%B3%C3%99%C2%81%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%98%C2%B7__en_3853612.html|title=Office Chrifien des Phosphates Group (OCP) Company Profile - Morocco {{!}} Financials & Key Executives {{!}} EMIS|website=www.emis.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.le360.ma/economie/ocp-group-reduit-sa-participation-dans-la-bcp-29317|title=OCP Group r\u00e9duit sa participation dans la BCP|website=fr.le360.ma|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Currently 95% of the OCP Group is owned by the Moroccan state and 5% by [[Banque Populaire du Maroc|Banque Centrale Populaire]] investment funds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/afrique/maroc-le-nouvel-age-d-or-des-phosphates_1072371.html|title=Maroc: le nouvel \u00e2ge d'or des phosphates|date=2012-01-17|website=LExpress.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.le360.ma/economie/ocp-group-reduit-sa-participation-dans-la-bcp-29317|title=OCP Group r\u00e9duit sa participation dans la BCP|website=fr.le360.ma|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate Timeline ===\n\n* '''1920''' Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates founded\n* '''1921''' Launch of mining production in Khouribga\n* '''1931''' Launch of mining production in Youssoufia\n* '''1965''' Launch of chemical production in Safi\n* '''1976''' Acquisition of 65% of Phosboucraa \n* '''1980''' Launch of mining production at Benguerir site\n* '''1984''' Launch of chemical production at Jorf Lasfar\n* '''1996''' Construction of purified phosphoric acid plant launched in Jorf Lasfar\n* '''2002''' OCP becomes sole owner of Phosboucraa\n* '''2006''' Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates becomes OCP \n* '''2008''' Transformation of Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates into a Corporation (OCP S.A)\n* '''2011''' Joint Venture with [[Jacobs Engineering Group|Jacobs Engineering]]\n* '''2013''' Joint Venture with [[DuPont|DuPont de Nemours]]\n* '''2014''' Launch of the Slurry Pipeline between Khouribga and Jorf Lasfar\n* '''2016''' Creation of OCP Africa\n* '''2018''' Inauguration of Mohammed VI Polytechnic University and Joint Venture with [[IBM]]\n\nIn 2007, the OCP Group set itself a target to triple its production of fertilizers by 2020.\n\nThe OCP Group plays an important economic and social role in Morocco. The value of phosphates and their derivatives represented nearly a quarter of the [[Economy of Morocco|country's exports]] and approximately 3.5% of the [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2010|title=Pr\u00e9sentation d'OCP|url=http://www.worldpolicyconference.com/presse.php?lien=sponsorpresse&&menu=2&&lang=fr&&edition=2010|journal=Site de la World Policy Conference|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130630162832/http://www.worldpolicyconference.com/presse.php?lien=sponsorpresse&&menu=2&&lang=fr&&edition=2010|archive-date=June 30, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=November 14, 2016|title=L'OCP: Le g\u00e9ant des phosphates made in Morocco|url=http://www.agrimaroc.ma/l-ocp-l-office-cherifien-des-phosphates/|journal=Agrimaroc}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[Fitch Ratings]] confirmed the rating of \"investment grade\" for the OCP Group.<ref>{{cite journal|date=December 15, 2016|title=Maroc : Fitch confirme l'Investment Grade \u00e0 OCP Group|url=http://www.lesafriques.com/actualite/maroc-fitch-confirme-l-investment-grade-a-ocp-group.html?Itemid=89?article=46364|journal=Les Afriques}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 15, 2016|title=Maroc : Fitch confirme l'Investment Grade \u00e0 OCP Group|url=https://www.afropages.fr/Les-Afriques/maroc-fitch-confirme-linvestment-grade-a-ocp-group|journal=Afropages|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113121650/https://www.afropages.fr/Les-Afriques/maroc-fitch-confirme-linvestment-grade-a-ocp-group|archive-date=January 13, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=April 3, 2014|title=Fitch Rates Morocco's OCP 'BBB-'; Proposed Notes 'BBB-(EXP)'|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFFit69584420140403|journal=Reuters Africa}}</ref>\n\nAfter approval from the AMMC ((Moroccan Authority of the Capital Market) Autorit\u00e9 Marocaine du March\u00e9 des Capitaux) on December 9, 2016, the OCP Group managed to reach 10.2&nbsp;billion [[Dirham|dirhams]] of bonds from the national community. This loan is the largest ever made in the Moroccan market.<ref>{{cite journal|date=December 23, 2016|title=Carton plein pour l'\u00e9mission obligataire d'OCP|url=http://telquel.ma/2016/12/23/banco-lemission-obligataire-docp_1528395|journal=Telquel}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 19, 2016|title=OCP cl\u00f4ture avec succ\u00e8s son \u00e9mission obligataire|url=http://www.leconomiste.com/flash-infos/ocp-cloture-avec-succes-son-emission-obligataire|journal=L'\u00e9conomiste}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=November 29, 2016|title=OCP : L'AMMC donne son feu vert \u00e0 un emprunt obligataire de 5 milliards de dirhams|url=https://www.yabiladi.com/articles/details/48810/l-ammc-donne-vert-emprunt-obligataire.html|journal=Yabiladi}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 14, 2014|title=OCP: \u00e9mission d'un emprunt obligataire de 5 milliards de dirhams|url=http://www.h24info.ma/economie/entreprises/ocp-emission-dun-emprunt-obligataire-de-5-milliards-de-dirhams/49090|journal=24h Info|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228082024/http://www.h24info.ma/economie/entreprises/ocp-emission-dun-emprunt-obligataire-de-5-milliards-de-dirhams/49090|archive-date=February 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 1, 2016|title=OCP finance l'expansion de son appareil productif et apure ses dettes|url=http://www.jeuneafrique.com/378734/economie/ocp-finance-lexpansion-de-appareil-productif-apure-dettes/|journal=Jeune Afrique}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the OCP Group created a new subsidiary named OCP Africa, which is responsible for leading the development of the group in the African fertilizer market through a network of subsidiaries in 12 African countries.\n\nIn the same year, OCP adopted a new internal culture, called \u2018Le Movement\u2019, aimed at re-focusing the group even more strongly on innovation.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gasteyger|first=Curt|title=Chapitre VII. Les armements dans le tiers-monde|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4000/books.iheid.4492|work=Les d\u00e9fis de la paix|pages=99\u2013109|publisher=Graduate Institute Publications|isbn=978-2-13-039917-9|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== Operations ==\n\n=== Mines and Key Sites ===\n\n==== Khouribga ====\nOCP\u2019s first mine opened in Khouribga in 1921. The [[Khouribga]] area has the richest phosphate deposits in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1163/_afco_asc_3086|title=Festival du Cin\u00e9ma Africain de Khouribga (Khouribga, Morocco)|website=African Studies Companion Online|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>In 2014, a [[slurry pipeline]] between Khouribga and [[Jorf Lasfar]] was launched, which transports phosphate from the mines to the processing facility safely and efficiently. The pipeline, one world\u2019s longest [[Pipeline transport|gravity powered pipelines]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rusconi|first=Julian|last2=Lakhouaja|first2=Anis|last3=Kopuz|first3=Mustafa|date=2016-01-01|title=The Design and Engineering of the 187 km Khouribga to Jorf Lasfar Phosphate Slurry Pipeline|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1877705816004367|journal=Procedia Engineering|series=SYMPHOS 2015 - 3rd International Symposium on Innovation and Technology in the Phosphate Industry|language=en|volume=138|pages=142\u2013150|doi=10.1016/j.proeng.2016.02.072|issn=1877-7058}}</ref> saves more than 3Mm3 of water per year, as well as a significant amount of energy.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/sites/default/files/2019-07/Sustainability%20report%202018%20OCP.pdf|title=2019 Sustainability Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>The site employs more people than any other OCP mine, which is more than 6,100 people.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2016, the mine produced 18.9[[Metric ton|MT]] of Phosphate Rock, or 70% of the total group output.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/sites/default/files/2018-11/RA%20OCP%202016%20VUK.pdf|title=2016 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the OCP Group started a new mining project in Sidi Chennane in the Khouribga area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1787/873102715006|title=Paraguay\u00a0: Croissance de la p\u00e9n\u00e9tration du mobile|website=dx.doi.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>The construction of the purified phosphoric acid plant was launched in Jorf Lasfar in 1996 and started production in 1998.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=El Falaki|first=K.|last2=Lhadi|first2=E. K.|date=2001|title=Contribution \u00e0 l\u2019\u00e9tude d\u2019impact de l\u2019\u00e9pandage d\u2019eaux us\u00e9es brutes sur l\u2019environnement dans la r\u00e9gion de Zemamra (province d\u2019El Jadida, Maroc)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4267/dechets-sciences-techniques.1399|journal=D\u00e9chets, sciences et techniques|issue=24|doi=10.4267/dechets-sciences-techniques.1399|issn=2268-7289}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the OCP Group inaugurated the slurry pipeline linking Khouribga to Jorf Lasfar, a technological advancement in the transportation of phosphates.<ref>{{Citation|last=de Blas|first=Ceferino|title=A cidade de Cunqueiro. Tres directores, tres d\u00e9cadas, un xornal|date=2015|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.17075/mucnoc.2014.063|work=Mil e un Cunqueiros. Novas olladas para un centenario|publisher=Consello da Cultura Galega|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, a fertilizer production plant dedicated entirely to Africa was inaugurated at Jorf Lasfar, the African Fertilizer Complex. Connected to the slurry pipeline, JFC 4 will be fully integrated and have its own thermoelectric plant. These plants not only make Jorf Lasfar completely energy self-sufficient, they also create an energy surplus that fuels the complex\u2019s sea water [[desalination]] station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/index.php/en/our-strategy/our-industrial-and-commercial-strategy/jorf-lasfar-largest-fertilizer-complex-world|title=Jorf Lasfar, the largest fertilizer complex in the world {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==== '''Gantour (Benguerir and Youssoufia)''' ====\nGantour is made up of two mining facilities, [[Ben Guerir|Benguerir]] and [[Youssoufia, Morocco|Youssoufia]] and holds the second largest amount of Morocco\u2019s phosphate reserves, 37% of the total.\n\nThe mine in Benguerir opened in 1980. It is situated 70km north of [[Marrakesh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mining-technology.com/projects/benguearir/|title=Moroccan Office Cherifi\u00e9n des Phosphates phosphate rock mine|website=Mining Technology {{!}} Mining News and Views Updated Daily|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 the mines\u2019 produced 6.3MT of [[Phosphorite|Phosphate Rock]], representing 23% of the group\u2019s total output.<ref name=\":2\" /> Since 2017 the mine has been one of Mohammed VI Polytechnic University\u2019s testing sites that is open to the scientific community and allows researchers from partner universities to test full-scale solutions in key areas. Called the \u201cAdvanced Mining Technology Platform,\u201d this pilot mine has many purposes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/en/our-strategy/our-industrial-and-commercial-strategy/benguerir-mine|title=The Benguerir Mine {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nRock from Benguerir is transported by rail to [[Safi, Morocco|Safi]] by [[ONCF]], the national railway company of Morocco. \n\nThe Group's activities are organised into an integrated model covering all operations of the value chain from the extraction of phosphates to the production and marketing of various products including fertilizers and phosphoric acid.<ref name=\"lexpress\">{{cite journal |title=Maroc: le nouvel \u00e2ge d'or des phosphates|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/afrique/maroc-le-nouvel-age-d-or-des-phosphates_1072371.html |journal=Jeune Afrique|date = January 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe mine in Youssoufia is the second most important mine to the Moroccan economy after the Khouribga mine. It is also the third biggest producer world wide of phosphate.<ref>{{Citation|title=Youssoufia (Maroc)|date=2020-02-08|url=https://fr.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Youssoufia_(Maroc)&oldid=167208539|work=Wikip\u00e9dia|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nSince 1998, OCP has also operated the [[Bouchane]] mine, which is situated 40km from Youssoufia. The phosphate from this mine is also processed at Youssoufia. \n\n==== '''Jorf Lasfar''' ====\nThe Jorf Lasfar processing platform is the largest fertilizer complex in the world. The first phase of the site opened in 1984 and has been expanded multiple times since. Products are made using phosphate rock mined in Khouribga. The site produced 4.63Mt of fertilizer in 2016, including, 1.86Mt [[Phosphoric acid]], 1.91Mt [[Ammonium dihydrogen phosphate|MAP]], and 1.14Mt [[Diammonium phosphate|DAP]]. Over 30 different of fertilizer were produced to suit various [[Soil type|soil types]]. The complex is made up of several units including the newest, the Africa fertilizer complex and JFC II.<ref name=\":2\" /> The site is the world\u2019s largest exporter of fertilizer. The site has a [[desalination plant]] with a capacity of 25[[\u33a3|Mm3]] per year \u2013 since its construction this has significantly reduced the amount of water consumed by the plant from local sources.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Safi ====\nThe first OCP chemical site, the Safi complex started its activities in 1965 to process the phosphate rock from Benguerir. In addition to ferilizser and phosphoric acid production unites the site has a phosphate washing unit and a sulfuric acid plant.\n\nIn 2016 the site produced 1.5Mt of phosphoric acid and 832.6Kt of [[Monocalcium phosphate|TSP fertilizer.]] These figures represented the highest production figures in the site\u2019s history.<ref name=\":2\" />The site produces fertilizer for both the domestic and international markets. \n\n==== '''Phosboucraa (Subsidiary)''' ====\nIn 1976, OCP acquired 65% of Phosboucraa mine ([[Bou Craa|Boucra\u00e2]]-[[Laayoune]]), and became the sole owner in 2002. \n\nOperations at the mine originally began in 1972; its activity includesmining, processing and marketing phosphate rock. Boucraa mine represents approximately 2% of the Morocco\u2019s total phosphate reserves, 4.6% of OCP Group\u2019s total revenue and around 8% of the total rock extracted.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://phosboucraa.ma/company/about-phosboucraa|title=PHOSBOUCRAA {{!}} About Phosboucraa|website=phosboucraa.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\n100% of profits made in the region are reinvested in the local community through the Phosboucraa Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/sites/default/files/2019-11/OCP_NIYA_communityReport.pdf|title=NIYA: Community Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Phosboucraa Foundation has so far helped more the 50,000 people through its various programs in education, health, and entrepreneurship.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nPhosboucraa\u2019s activities are located in 3 different places:\n\n* [[Mining]] activities are located 140 km away by road from La\u00e2youne, thus far from any possible shipping area\n* The processing plant and the wharf are located at [[Atlantic Ocean|La\u00e2youne beach]], 20 km away from the city. A 102 km long [[conveyor belt]] is used for transporting phosphates from the Mine to La\u00e2youne beach\n* Headquarters are located in La\u00e2youne city\n\nTo help develop the value chain at this site OCP is investing $2.2billion to build a phosphate processing plant, producing fertilizer and phosphoric acid. The scheme is expected to create more than 5,000 job in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.phosboucraa.ma/company/key-figures/industrial-investments|title=PHOSBOUCRAA {{!}} Industrial Investments|website=www.phosboucraa.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nThe project will continue the groups policy of hiring local workers, which now make up 76% of the workforce, up from just 4% in 1976. This has been achieved through outreach and training programs, upskilling locals to take on these roles. These schemes have also led to hundreds of workers being trained to do skilled work at the groups site in the North.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.phosboucraa.ma/company/|title=Company|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== OCP Globally ==\n\n==== OCP Africa ====\nIn February 2016, the OCP Group created a new subsidiary named OCP Africa, which is responsible for leading the development of the group on the African fertilizer market through a network of subsidiaries in 5 African countries. The subsidiary was granted the status of Casablanca Finance City (CFC) for investors on the African continent to benefit from an attractive package of tax incentives and other opportunities.<ref name=Agefi>{{cite journal |title=Trading \u00e0 Gen\u00e8ve pour le g\u00e9ant marocain des phosphates|url=http://www.agefi.com/quotidien-agefi/suisse/detail/edition/2016-06-03/article/ocp-loffice-cherifien-des-phosphates-vient-douvrir-une-entite-de-negoce-en-suisse-sous-le-nom-de-saftco--428186.html|journal=Agefi|date = June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Group launches new subsidiary|url=http://www.africanfarming.net/crops/agriculture/ocp-group-launches-new-subsidiary|journal=African Farming|date = March 30, 2016}}</ref> The OCP projects in Africa cover the entire value chain, including the local construction of fertilizer plants, the development of logistics and distribution capabilities, as well as investment in research for the development of formulas adapted for the soils and crops (mapping the African soil fertility and respective fertilizer needs). The African Development Bank (ADB) has pledged to support the various initiatives of the OCP Group in favour of the African continent.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Maroc : Akinwumi Adesina chez Terrab, PDG OCP Group|url=http://www.lesafriques.com/actualite/maroc-akinwumi-adesina-chez-terrab-pdg-ocp-group.html?Itemid=89|journal=Les Afriques|date = July 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Le groupe OCP lance sa filiale OCP Africa pour renforcer le d\u00e9veloppement agricole de l'Afrique |url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/02/25/ocp-africa-nouvelle-filiale-developpement-agricole_n_9318388.html |journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = February 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=C\u00f4te d'Ivoire/International/ Le PDG du Groupe OCP re\u00e7oit le Pr\u00e9sident du Groupe de la BAD (Communiqu\u00e9)|url=http://news.abidjan.net/h/595029.html|journal=Abidjan.net|date = July 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=A la COP 22, l'accord sur l'agriculture en friche|url=http://www.liberation.fr/planete/2016/11/17/a-la-cop-22-l-accord-sur-l-agriculture-en-friche_1529165|journal=Lib\u00e9ration|date = November 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe OCP Group plans to open 14 new branches in Sub-Saharan Africa to make a promising entry into the African market. The main countries targeted by this operation are: [[C\u00f4te d\u2019Ivoire]], [[Senegal]], [[the Democratic Republic of Congo]], [[Benin]], [[Cameroon]], Nigeria, [[Tanzania]], [[Angola]], [[Zambia]], [[Zimbabwe]], [[Mozambique]], [[Kenya]], [[Ghana]], and [[Ethiopia]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Maroc : le groupe OCP pr\u00e9voit 14 nouvelles filiales en Afrique subsaharienne|url=http://www.financialafrik.com/2016/08/05/maroc-le-groupe-ocp-prevoit-14-nouvelles-filiales-en-afrique-subsaharienne/|journal=Financial Afrik|date = August 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Nigeria]] ====\nIn 2016, the Morrocan head of state and King Mohammed VI presided over the ceremony marking the launch of a strategic partnership for the development of the fertilizer industry in Nigeria. In particular, this partnership includes an agreement between the OCP Group and Dangote Industries Limited for creating a platform for fertilizer production in Nigeria. Similarly, an agreement for developing the fertilizer market was signed between the OCP Group and the association of fertilizer producers and suppliers in Nigeria.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Maroc/Nig\u00e9ria : Plusieurs accords sign\u00e9s aujourd'hui, les d\u00e9tails|url=http://www.infomediaire.net/news/maroc/marocnigeria-plusieurs-accords-signes-aujourdhui-les-details|journal=Infom\u00e9diaire|date=December 2, 2016}}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi et le Chef de l'Etat nig\u00e9rian pr\u00e9sident la c\u00e9r\u00e9monie de lancement d'un partenariat strat\u00e9gique pour le d\u00e9veloppement de l'industrie des engrais au Nig\u00e9ria|url=http://www.mapexpress.ma/actualite/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-et-le-chef-de-letat-nigerian-president-la-ceremonie-de-lancement-dun-partenariat-strategique-pour-le-developpement-de-lindustrie-des-engrais-au-nigeria/|journal=MA Express|date = December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Accord OCP-Dangote: quand le premier producteur mondial d\u2019engrais tend la main \u00e0 l\u2019homme le plus riche d\u2019Afrique|url=http://www.financialafrik.com/2016/12/03/accord-ocp-dangote-quand-le-premier-producteur-mondial-dengrais-tend-la-main-a-lhomme-le-plus-riche-dafrique/#.WIHjALbhDUI|journal=Financial Afrik|date = December 3, 2016}}</ref> Likewise, a pipeline project linking Nigeria to Morocco, passing through several countries in West Africa, is about to take shape.<ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi pr\u00e9side \u00e0 Casablanca une s\u00e9ance de travail consacr\u00e9e au projet de gazoduc, reliant le Nig\u00e9ria au Maroc \u00e0 travers plusieurs pays d'Afrique de l'ouest |url=http://www.mapexpress.ma/actualite/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-preside-a-casablanca-une-seance-de-travail-consacree-au-projet-de-gazoduc-reliant-le-nigeria-au-maroc-a-travers-plusieurs-pays-dafrique-de-louest-cabinet-royal/|journal=Agence de presse marocaine|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi pr\u00e9side \u00e0 Casablanca une s\u00e9ance de travail consacr\u00e9e au projet de gazoduc, reliant le Nig\u00e9ria au Maroc \u00e0 travers plusieurs pays d'Afrique de l'ouest|url=http://www.maroc.ma/fr/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-preside-casablanca-une-seance-de-travail-consacree-au-projet-de-gazoduc|journal=Maroc|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Alerte : Le Maroc passe \u00e0 l'acte pour le gazoduc g\u00e9ant, r\u00e9union royale \u00e0 Casablanca|url=http://www.infomediaire.net/news/maroc/alerte-le-maroc-passe-lacte-pour-le-gazoduc-geant-reunion-royale-casablanca|journal=InfoM\u00e9diaire|date=December 13, 2016|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217064419/http://www.infomediaire.net/news/maroc/alerte-le-maroc-passe-lacte-pour-le-gazoduc-geant-reunion-royale-casablanca|archive-date=February 17, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Gazoduc nig\u00e9ria-maroc: le roi pr\u00e9side une s\u00e9ance de travail sur la faisabilit\u00e9 et le financement |url=http://www.bladi.info/threads/gazoduc-nigeria-maroc-roi-preside.445289/|journal=Bladi|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Mohammed VI \u00e9tudie la faisabilit\u00e9 technique et le financement du projet de gazoduc|url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/12/13/mohammed-vi-etudie-faisabilite-technique-financement-projet-gazoduc_n_13606152.html?ir=Maroc|journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Rwanda]] ====\nIn October 2016, during the visit of King Mohammed VI, the Ministry of Agriculture and Animal Resources signed an agreement with the OCP Group for the construction of a fertilizer plant in the country to facilitate access to these local farmers.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Rwanda's move towards green agric gains momentum|url=http://www.newtimes.co.rw/section/article/2016-12-11/206163/|journal=The New Times|date = December 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Saftco ===\nOn May 25, 2016, the OCP Group opened a commodity trading entity in Switzerland that includes phosphate, fertilizers and chemical products.<ref name=Agefi/><ref>{{cite journal |title=L'Office ch\u00e9rifien des phosphates ouvre une filiale \u00e0 Gen\u00e8ve|url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/06/03/ocp-geneve-maroc_n_10274720.html|journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = June 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Financial information ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n |+ Figures 2009 \u2013 2018\n |-\n |\n !scope=\"col\"| 2009\n !scope=\"col\"| 2010\n !scope=\"col\"| 2011\n !scope=\"col\"| 2012\n !scope=\"col\"| 2013\n !scope=\"col\"| 2014\n !scope=\"col\"| 2015\n !scope=\"col\"| 2016\n !scope=\"col\"| 2017\n !scope=\"col\"| 2018 \n |-\n !scope=\"row\"| Turnover (billions of MAD)\n | 25.3\n | 43.5\n | 56.4\n | 59.4\n |46.2\n |41.4\n |47.7\n |42.5\n |48.5\n |55.9\n|-\n ! scope=\"row\" | Profit (billions of MAD)\n | 1.3\n | 8.8\n | 16.3\n | 14.1\n |7.1\n |7.6\n |\n |\n |\n |5.4\n |\n |}\n\n== Executives (2016) ==\n\n=== Top Management ===\n* Chairman & CEO: [[Mostafa Terrab]]\n\n=== Senior Management ===\n* Executive vice president strategy & corporate development : Marouane Ameziane\n* Executive vice president sales & marketing : Mohamed Belhoussain\n* Executive vice president legal & corporate affairs : Otmane Bennani-Smires\n* Executive vice president human capital: Faris Derrij\n* Executive vice president industrial development: Abdelaziz El Mallah\n* Executive vice president industrial operations: Iliass Elfali\n* Executive vice president performance Management : Nada Elmajdoub\n* Executive vice president chief financial officer: Ghislane Guedira\n* Executive vice president digital office : Mohamed Laklalech\n* Executive vice president Africa : Karim Lotfi Senhadji\n\n== 2020 coronavirus crisis response ==\nOCP Group contributed $310 million the Moroccan emergency fund, created by [[Mohammed VI of Morocco|King Mohammed IV]] on 15 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2020/03/296549/moroccan-government-members-donate-salaries-to-covid-19-fund/|title=Moroccan Government Members Donate Salaries to COVID-19 Fund|last=Hekking|first=Morgan|date=2020-03-17|website=Morocco World News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-morocco-idUSKBN212173|title=Morocco to create $1 billion fund to counter coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-03-15|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ocpgroup.ma/en Official website of the OCP Group]\n* [http://www.ocpafrica.com/ Official website of OCP Africa]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Economy of Morocco]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Office Cherifien des Phosphates}}\n[[Category:1920 establishments in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Phosphate mining]]\n[[Category:Fertilizer companies of Morocco]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of Morocco]]\n[[Category:Mining companies of Morocco]]\n", "name_user": "WonderingCamel", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OCP_Group"}
{"title_page": "NHS trust", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=NHS England trusts|2=Talk:NHS trust#Requested move 19 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>An '''NHS trust''' is an organisational unit within the [[National Health Service (England)|English National Health Service]], generally serving either a geographical area or a specialised function (such as an ambulance service). In any particular location there may be several trusts involved in the different aspects of providing healthcare to the local population. {{As of|2020|April}} there are altogether 217 trusts, and they employ around 800,000 of the NHS's 1.2 million staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nhsproviders.org/confronting-coronavirus-in-the-nhs/foreword|title=Confronting coronavirus in the NHS: Foreword|last=Hopson|first=Chris|date=15 April 2020|website=[[NHS Providers]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Nature of a trust==\nNHS trusts were established under the [[National Health Service and Community Care Act 1990]] and were set up in five waves.  Each one was established by a [[Statutory Instrument]].\n\nThe trusts are not [[Trust law|trusts]] in the legal sense but are in effect public sector corporations. Each trust is headed by a [[board of directors|board]] consisting of [[executive director|executive]] and [[non-executive director]]s, and is [[chairman|chaired]] by a non-executive director. There were about 2,200 non-executives across 470 organisations in the NHS in England in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Make the most of non-executives and the independent sector|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/resource-centre/supplements/supplement-make-the-most-of-non-executives-and-the-independent-sector/5085356.article#.VYFl2ba_UYA|accessdate=17 June 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=28 May 2015}}</ref> Non-executive directors are recruited by open advertisement. All trusts ([[NHS foundation trust|foundation trusts]] and those which have yet to reach foundation trust status) are regulated by [[NHS Improvement]]. Board members are, from November 2014, subject to a [[fit and proper person test]].\n\nAll trust boards are required to have an audit committee consisting only of non-executive directors, on which the chair may not sit. This committee is entrusted not only with the supervision of financial [[audit]], but of systems of [[corporate governance]] within the trust.  Hospital board members have a duty to act on signals of poor performance on quality and safety data, and yet many of the papers presented to them have been found to be lacking good data visualisations.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Schmidtke|first1=Kelly Ann|last2=Poots|first2=Alan J|last3=Carpio|first3=Juan|last4=Vlaev|first4=Ivo|last5=Kandala|first5=Ngianga-Bakwin|last6=Lilford|first6=Richard J|title=Considering chance in quality and safety performance measures: an analysis of performance reports by boards in English NHS trusts|journal=BMJ Quality & Safety|date=31 March 2016|pages=bmjqs-2015-004967|doi=10.1136/bmjqs-2015-004967|url=http://qualitysafety.bmj.com/content/early/2016/03/31/bmjqs-2015-004967.abstract}}</ref>\n\nThe [[High Court of Justice]] decided in December 2019 that NHS trusts were not charities for the purposes of the [[Local Government Finance Act 1988]], so they have to pay [[Business rates in England|business rates]] at the full rate.<ref>{{cite news |title=Councils welcome \u2018common sense\u2019 tax victory over NHS trusts |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/finance-and-efficiency/councils-welcome-common-sense-tax-victory-over-nhs-trusts/7026552.article? |accessdate=23 February 2020 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=12 December 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Future development==\nIn September 2015 [[Jeremy Hunt]] was reported as saying \u201cI think we do have too many trusts as independent organisations\" in a context where mergers between trusts and the establishment of chains of hospitals were being discussed.<ref>{{cite news|title=The NHS has 'too many trusts', says Hunt|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/news/acute-care/the-nhs-has-too-many-trusts-says-hunt/5090168.article#.VilPbkpup1A|accessdate=22 October 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=9 September 2015}}</ref>  Subsequently [[Simon Stevens (civil servant)|Simon Stevens]] made it clear that he did not expect the remaining NHS trusts to become Foundation Trusts, saying \"We are frankly kidding ourselves if we think the non-FTs are going to pass the kinds of criteria that have been set by [[Monitor (NHS)|Monitor]].\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Stevens: Funding growth may depend on 'transformation' plans|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/news/finance/stevens-funding-growth-may-depend-on-transformation-plans/5091115.article#.VilQy0pup1A|accessdate=22 October 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=13 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Types==\nThere are several types of NHS trusts:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhs.uk/NHSEngland/thenhs/about/Pages/authoritiesandtrusts.aspx|title=NHS authorities and trusts|date=28 January 2013|work=The NHS in England|publisher=NHS Choices|accessdate=7 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n*[[Hospital trust]] (also known as an '''acute trust'''), which provides [[secondary care]] services\n*[[Mental health trust]]\n*[[Ambulance services trust]]\n*[[Community health trust]]\n\nOver time the distinction between different types has eroded, and both hospital and mental health trusts have taken on responsibility for various community services.  [[Sustainability and transformation plan]]s all propose to move services out of hospitals into the community and the hospital trusts are generally planning to follow these initiatives.\n\n===Foundation trusts===\n{{Main|NHS foundation trust}}\nFoundation trust status may be applied for by the above categories of NHS trust. Successive governments have announced that all NHS Trusts should become NHS Foundation Trusts, and deadlines have been set for this transformation, which have repeatedly been missed.{{cn|date=November 2013}}\n\n===Former types===\n\n*[[NHS primary care trust]] (PCT) (abolished 1 April 2013), which provided [[primary care]] services, public health functions and commissioned [[secondary care]] services\n*[[NHS care trust]] (abolished 1 April 2013), provided/commissioned health and social care services, usually with responsibilities of both a PCT and a [[Local government in England|local authority]]\n\n==Other types of NHS organisation==\nSeveral [[NHS special health authority|special health authorities]], organised on a national basis, deal with NHS-wide issues. An example is [[NHS Blood and Transplant]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of NHS trusts]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n\n[[Category:NHS trusts| ]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=NHS England trusts|2=Talk:NHS trust#Requested move 19 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>An '''NHS trust''' is an organisational unit within the [[National Health Service (England)|English National Health Service]], generally serving either a geographical area or a specialised function (such as an ambulance service). In any particular location there may be several trusts involved in the different aspects of providing healthcare to the local population. {{As of|2020|April}} there are altogether 217 trusts, and they employ around 800,000 of the NHS's 1.2 million staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nhsproviders.org/confronting-coronavirus-in-the-nhs/foreword|title=Confronting coronavirus in the NHS: Foreword|last=Hopson|first=Chris|date=15 April 2020|website=[[NHS Providers]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Nature of a trust==\nNHS trusts were established under the [[National Health Service and Community Care Act 1990]] and were set up in five waves.  Each one was established by a [[Statutory Instrument]].\n\nThe trusts are not [[Trust law|trusts]] in the legal sense but are in effect public sector corporations. Each trust is headed by a [[board of directors|board]] consisting of [[executive director|executive]] and [[non-executive director]]s, and is [[chairman|chaired]] by a non-executive director. There were about 2,200 non-executives across 470 organisations in the NHS in England in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Make the most of non-executives and the independent sector|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/resource-centre/supplements/supplement-make-the-most-of-non-executives-and-the-independent-sector/5085356.article#.VYFl2ba_UYA|accessdate=17 June 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=28 May 2015}}</ref> Non-executive directors are recruited by open advertisement. All trusts ([[NHS foundation trust|foundation trusts]] and those which have yet to reach foundation trust status) are regulated by [[NHS Improvement]]. Board members are, from November 2014, subject to a [[fit and proper person test]].\n\nAll trust boards are required to have an audit committee consisting only of non-executive directors, on which the chair may not sit. This committee is entrusted not only with the supervision of financial [[audit]], but of systems of [[corporate governance]] within the trust.  Hospital board members have a duty to act on signals of poor performance on quality and safety data, and yet many of the papers presented to them have been found to be lacking good data visualisations.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Schmidtke|first1=Kelly Ann|last2=Poots|first2=Alan J|last3=Carpio|first3=Juan|last4=Vlaev|first4=Ivo|last5=Kandala|first5=Ngianga-Bakwin|last6=Lilford|first6=Richard J|title=Considering chance in quality and safety performance measures: an analysis of performance reports by boards in English NHS trusts|journal=BMJ Quality & Safety|date=31 March 2016|pages=bmjqs-2015-004967|doi=10.1136/bmjqs-2015-004967|url=http://qualitysafety.bmj.com/content/early/2016/03/31/bmjqs-2015-004967.abstract}}</ref>\n\nThe [[High Court of Justice]] decided in December 2019 that NHS trusts were not charities for the purposes of the [[Local Government Finance Act 1988]], so they have to pay [[Business rates in England|business rates]] at the full rate.<ref>{{cite news |title=Councils welcome \u2018common sense\u2019 tax victory over NHS trusts |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/finance-and-efficiency/councils-welcome-common-sense-tax-victory-over-nhs-trusts/7026552.article? |accessdate=23 February 2020 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=12 December 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Future development==\nIn September 2015 [[Jeremy Hunt]] was reported as saying \u201cI think we do have too many trusts as independent organisations\" in a context where mergers between trusts and the establishment of chains of hospitals were being discussed.<ref>{{cite news|title=The NHS has 'too many trusts', says Hunt|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/news/acute-care/the-nhs-has-too-many-trusts-says-hunt/5090168.article#.VilPbkpup1A|accessdate=22 October 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=9 September 2015}}</ref>  Subsequently [[Simon Stevens (civil servant)|Simon Stevens]] made it clear that he did not expect the remaining NHS trusts to become Foundation Trusts, saying \"We are frankly kidding ourselves if we think the non-FTs are going to pass the kinds of criteria that have been set by [[Monitor (NHS)|Monitor]].\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Stevens: Funding growth may depend on 'transformation' plans|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/news/finance/stevens-funding-growth-may-depend-on-transformation-plans/5091115.article#.VilQy0pup1A|accessdate=22 October 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=13 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Types==\nThere are several types of NHS trusts:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhs.uk/NHSEngland/thenhs/about/Pages/authoritiesandtrusts.aspx|title=NHS authorities and trusts|date=28 January 2013|work=The NHS in England|publisher=NHS Choices|accessdate=7 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n*[[Hospital trust]] (also known as an '''acute trust'''), which provides [[secondary care]] services\n*[[NHS mental health trust]]\n*[[Ambulance services trust]]\n*[[Community health NHS Trust]]\n\nOver time the distinction between different types has eroded, and both hospital and mental health trusts have taken on responsibility for various community services.  [[Sustainability and transformation plan]]s all propose to move services out of hospitals into the community and the hospital trusts are generally planning to follow these initiatives.\n\n===Foundation trusts===\n{{Main|NHS foundation trust}}\nFoundation trust status may be applied for by the above categories of NHS trust. Successive governments have announced that all NHS Trusts should become NHS Foundation Trusts, and deadlines have been set for this transformation, which have repeatedly been missed.{{cn|date=November 2013}}\n\n===Former types===\n\n*[[NHS primary care trust]] (PCT) (abolished 1 April 2013), which provided [[primary care]] services, public health functions and commissioned [[secondary care]] services\n*[[NHS care trust]] (abolished 1 April 2013), provided/commissioned health and social care services, usually with responsibilities of both a PCT and a [[Local government in England|local authority]]\n\n==Other types of NHS organisation==\nSeveral [[NHS special health authority|special health authorities]], organised on a national basis, deal with NHS-wide issues. An example is [[NHS Blood and Transplant]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of NHS trusts]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n\n[[Category:NHS trusts| ]]\n", "name_user": "Millstream3", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTypes:Update the names to match the current names of the articles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NHS_trust"}
