"center\"|\n|-\n!12\n|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n|data-sort-value=\"\"|{{flagicon|}}\n|data-sort-value=\"\"|{{flagicon|}}\n|data-sort-value=\"\"|{{flagicon|}}\n|data-sort-value=\"\"|{{flagicon|}}\n|align=center|[[2020 Brazilian Grand Prix|Report]]\n|align=\"center\"|\n|-\n!13\n|data-sort-value=\"abu\"|{{flagicon|UAE}} [[Abu Dhabi Grand Prix]]\n|data-sort-value=\"\"|{{flagicon|}}\n|data-sort-value=\"\"|{{flagicon|}}\n|data-sort-value=\"\"|{{flagicon|}}\n|data-sort-value=\"\"|{{flagicon|}}\n|align=center|[[2020 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix|Report]]\n|align=\"center\"|\n|-\n|}\n<!--===Scoring system===\n{{further|List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems}}\nPoints are awarded to the top ten classified drivers and the driver who set the fastest lap. The driver with fastest lap has to be within the top 10 to receive the point. The points are awarded for every race using the following system:<ref name=\"points regs\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fia.com/file/78014/download/26183|title=2019 Formula One Sporting Regulations|last=|first=|date=12 March 2019|website=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|fia]].com|pages=3\u20134, 41|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313225312/https://www.fia.com/file/78014/download/26183|archive-date=13 March 2019|access-date=27 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%; text-align:center\"\n!Position\n!style=\"background-color:#ffffbf\"|&nbsp;1st&nbsp;\n!style=\"background-color:#dfdfdf\"|&nbsp;2nd&nbsp;\n!style=\"background-color:#ffdf9f\"|&nbsp;3rd&nbsp;\n!style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|&nbsp;4th&nbsp;\n!style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|&nbsp;5th&nbsp;\n!style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|&nbsp;6th&nbsp;\n!style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|&nbsp;7th&nbsp;\n!style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|&nbsp;8th&nbsp;\n!style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|&nbsp;9th&nbsp;\n!style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|&nbsp;10th&nbsp;\n!&nbsp;[[Fastest lap|FL]]&nbsp;\n|-\n!Points\n|style=\"background-color:#ffffbf\"|25\n|style=\"background-color:#dfdfdf\"|18\n|style=\"background-color:#ffdf9f\"|15\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|12\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|10\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|8\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|6\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|4\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|2\n|style=\"background-color:#dfffdf\"|1\n|1\n|}\n\n===World Drivers' Championship standings===\n{{F1 Drivers Standings}}\n\n===World Constructors' Championship standings===\n{{F1 Constructors Standings}}\n-->\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|https://www.formula1.com/}}\n\n{{Formula One Championship}}\n\n{{World championships in 2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Formula One| ]]\n[[Category:Formula One seasons]]\n[[Category:Scheduled motorsport seasons|Formula One season 2020]]\n", "name_user": "85.66.213.30", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eTechnical regulations)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Formula_One_World_Championship"}
{"title_page": "Bampton Classical Opera", "text_new": "[[Image:Westonbirthousemorris edited.jpg|thumb|300px|Westonbirt House, one of Bampton Classical Opera's main performing venues]]\n'''Bampton Classical Opera''' is an [[opera]] company based in [[Bampton, Oxfordshire|Bampton]], [[Oxfordshire]] specialising in the production of lesser known opera from the [[Classical period (music)|Classical period]]. Performances are always sung in English.\n\nBampton Classical Opera was founded in 1993 by its current artistic directors, Gilly French and Jeremy Gray, in order to perform classical period opera in English. It works with a variety of conductors and ensembles and does not have a permanent music director. It performs with both modern and period instrument orchestras and has often appeared with the [[London Mozart Players]] and Chroma Ensemble. It particularly aims to provide performances for young singers.\n\nThe company's staged opera productions are performed in a garden setting in Bampton and at [[Westonbirt House]], the premises of [[Westonbirt School]], as well as at [[St John's, Smith Square]], London. From time to time it tours to other UK venues and festivals, which have included the [[Wigmore Hall]] and the [[Purcell Room]] in London, the [[Buxton Festival]], the [[Cheltenham Music Festival]] and others. In addition, occasional concerts are performed including an annual one in [[St Mary\u2019s Church, Bampton]] usually on 21 December, with other concerts in Oxford and London.\n[[Image:Marcos Portugal's Marriage of Figaro, Bampton 2010.jpg|left|thumb|300px|John-Colyn Gyeantey (the Count) and Emily Rowley Jones (Susanna) in the UK premi\u00e8re of Marcos Portugal\u2019s ''Marriage of Figaro'', Bampton 2010]]\n[[Image:Arne Paris Bampton.jpg|left|thumb|300px|Catherine Backhouse (Pallas Athena), Aoife O'Sullivan (Venus), Barbara Cole Walton (Juno) in Bampton Classical Opera's 2016 production of Thomas Arne's ''Judgment of Paris'']]\n\nIn 2020 the company plans to perform ''[[Paride ed Elena|Paris and Helen]]'' by [[Christoph Willibald Gluck|C W Gluck]].<ref>[https://www.bamptonopera.org/events.htm  Bampton Classical Opera, What's On]</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Bampton Classical Opera performed the [[United Kingdom]] premi\u00e8re of ''The Philosopher's Stone'' (''[[Der Stein der Weisen]]''), a [[singspiel]] by [[Emanuel Schikaneder]] composed in collaboration with [[Mozart]], [[Johann Baptist Henneberg|Henneberg]], [[Benedikt Schack|Schack]], and [[Franz Xaver Gerl|Gerl]]. In 2004, it gave the first UK staged performance of [[Antonio Salieri|Salieri]]'s ''[[Falstaff_(Salieri)|Falstaff]]'', and in July 2007 staged the UK premi\u00e8re of [[Georg Benda]]'s ''[[Romeo und Julie|Romeo and Juliet]]''. It also performed the [[Mozart]] arrangement of [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]]'s ''[[Acis and Galatea (Handel)|Acis and Galatea]]''. In 2008 it presented ''[[Leonora (opera)|Leonora]]'' by [[Ferdinando Paer]], based on the same story as ''[[Fidelio]]'', and in 2009 ''[[Le pescatrici|Le Pescatrici]]'' (''The Fisherwomen'') by [[Haydn]]. In 2010, it presented the UK premi\u00e8re of [[Marcos Portugal]]'s ''The Marriage of Figaro'' (1799), and [[Alfred (Arne opera)|''The Masque of King Alfred'']] and [[The Judgement of Paris (opera)|''The Judgment of Paris'']] by [[Thomas Arne]]. In 2011, it presented more performances of the Arne double-bill; ''Il parnaso confuso'' by [[Gluck]]; ''[[The Italian Girl in London]]'' (''L'italiana in Londra'') by [[Domenico Cimarosa|Cimarosa]], first performed in 1778; and [[The Choice of Hercules (Handel)|''The Choice of Hercules'']] by [[Handel]]. In 2012, it presented a revival of Marcos Portugal's ''The Marriage of Figaro'' and new productions of ''[[L'amant jaloux]] (The Jealous Lover)'' by [[Andr\u00e9 Gr\u00e9try]] (1778) and ''[[Blaise le savetier]] (Blaise the Cobbler)'' (1759) by [[Fran\u00e7ois-Andr\u00e9 Danican Philidor]]. In 2013, it presented a new production of Mozart\u2019s first comic opera, ''[[La finta semplice]]'' (1769), in a new English translation, ''Pride and Pretence''. In 2014, it revisited ''[[La finta semplice]]'' and Gluck's ''[[Il Parnaso confuso|Il parnaso confuso]]'', as well as presenting ''[https://www.bamptonopera.org/operadetail.htm?opera=32 Orfeo]'' by [[Ferdinando Bertoni]]. In 2015, Bampton Classical Opera performed Salieri's ''[[La grotta di Trofonio|Trofonio's Cave]]''. In 2016, it staged a double bill called the ''Divine Comedies'' featuring Arne's ''[[The Judgement of Paris (opera)|The Judgement of Paris]]'' and Gluck's ''Philemon and Baucis'' - an English translation of part two of ''[[Le feste d'Apollo]]''. In 2017, it presented ''[https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2017/salieris-school-jealousy-review-st-johns-smith-square/ The School of Jealousy]'' by Salieri. In 2018, it presented Isouard's ''[[Cendrillon (Isouard)|Cinderella]]'' and Menotti's ''[[Amahl and the Night Visitors]]''. In 2019, it performed ''[https://bamptonopera.org/brideandgloom.htm Bride and Gloom (Gli sposi malcontenti)]'' by [[Stephen Storace]] in an English translation by [[Brian Trowell]].<ref>[https://www.bamptonopera.org/archive.htm  Bampton Classical Opera, Past Productions]</ref>\n[[Image:Stephen Storace's Gli sposi malcontenti, 2019 performance (as 'Bride & Gloom') by Bampton Classical Opera.png|thumb|300px|Stephen Storace's ''Gli sposi malcontenti'', 2019 performance (as ''Bride & Gloom'')]]\n\nThe company's patrons are [[Bonaventura Bottone]], [[Brian Kay]], Sir [[Roger Norrington]], [[Andrew Parrott]], Sir [[David Pountney]], Sir [[Curtis Price]] and [[Jean Rigby]].<ref>[https://www.bamptonopera.org/index.htm  Bampton Classical Opera]</ref> Dame [[Felicity Lott]], the late Sir [[Charles Mackerras]] and the late Sir [[Philip Ledger]] were also patrons, as was the Rt Hon [[David Cameron]], in whose former [[Witney (UK Parliament constituency)|Witney]] constituency Bampton lies.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n*Jones, Roger, Review of Thomas Arne's ''Masque of King Alfred'' and ''The Judgment of Paris'', [http://www.musicweb-international.com/sandh/2010/Jul-Dec10/arne0711.htm ''MusicWeb International''] 7 November 2010 (accessed 29 January 2011)\n*Church, Michael, Review of Benda's ''Romeo and Juliet'' at Bampton Classical Opera, [http://arts.independent.co.uk/music/reviews/article2980490.ece ''The Independent''] 20 September 2007 (accessed 24 September 2007)\n*Tanner, Michael, Review of ''Acis and Galatea'', [http://www.spectator.co.uk/arts-and-culture/featured/31052/part_3/laughter-unbecoming.thtml ''Spectator''] 24 May 2007 (accessed 29 January 2011)\n*Porter, Andrew, Review of [[Vicente Mart\u00edn y Soler|Mart\u00edn y Soler]]'s ''La scuola dei maritati'' at Bampton Classical Opera, [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/incomingFeeds/article617035.ece ''The Times''] 18 August 2006 (accessed 22 June 2007)\n*Thicknesse, Robert, Review of [[Giovanni Paisiello|Paisiello]]'s ''The Barber of Seville'' at Bampton Classical Opera, [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/article546151.ece ''The Times''] 21 July 2005 (accessed 22 June 2007)\n*Thicknesse, Robert, Review of French double bill, Bampton Opera, [http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/leisure/music_and_books/music/9838988.French_double_bill__Bampton_Opera__The_Deanery_Gardens__Bampton ''Oxford Times''] 26 July 2012 (accessed 23 August 2012)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bamptonopera.org Bampton Classical Opera website]\n[[Category:British opera companies]]\n[[Category:Opera in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Opera in London]]\n[[Category:Opera festivals]]\n[[Category:Classical music festivals in England]]\n[[Category:Music festivals in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Westonbirthousemorris edited.jpg|thumb|300px|Westonbirt House, one of Bampton Classical Opera's main performing venues]]\n'''Bampton Classical Opera''' is an [[opera]] company based in [[Bampton, Oxfordshire|Bampton]], [[Oxfordshire]] specialising in the production of lesser known opera from the [[Classical period (music)|Classical period]]. Performances are always sung in English.\n\nBampton Classical Opera was founded in 1993 by its current artistic directors, Gilly French and Jeremy Gray, in order to perform classical period opera in English. It works with a variety of conductors and ensembles and does not have a permanent music director. It performs with both modern and period instrument orchestras and has often appeared with the [[London Mozart Players]] and Chroma Ensemble. It particularly aims to provide performances for young singers.\n\nThe company's staged opera productions are performed in a garden setting in Bampton and at [[Westonbirt House]], the premises of [[Westonbirt School]], as well as at [[St John's, Smith Square]], London. From time to time it tours to other UK venues and festivals, which have included the [[Wigmore Hall]] and the [[Purcell Room]] in London, the [[Buxton Festival]], the [[Cheltenham Music Festival]] and others. In addition, occasional concerts are performed including an annual one in [[St Mary\u2019s Church, Bampton]] usually on 21 December, with other concerts in Oxford and London.\n[[Image:Marcos Portugal's Marriage of Figaro, Bampton 2010.jpg|left|thumb|300px|John-Colyn Gyeantey (the Count) and Emily Rowley Jones (Susanna) in the UK premi\u00e8re of Marcos Portugal\u2019s ''Marriage of Figaro'', Bampton 2010]]\n[[Image:Arne Paris Bampton.jpg|left|thumb|300px|Catherine Backhouse (Pallas Athena), Aoife O'Sullivan (Venus), Barbara Cole Walton (Juno) in Bampton Classical Opera's 2016 production of Thomas Arne's ''Judgment of Paris'']]\n\nIn 2020 the company plans to perform ''[[Paride ed Elena|Paris and Helen]]'' by [[Christoph Willibald Gluck|C W Gluck]].<ref>[https://www.bamptonopera.org/events.htm  Bampton Classical Opera, What's On]</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Bampton Classical Opera performed the [[United Kingdom]] premi\u00e8re of ''The Philosopher's Stone'' (''[[Der Stein der Weisen]]''), a [[singspiel]] by [[Emanuel Schikaneder]] composed in collaboration with [[Mozart]], [[Johann Baptist Henneberg|Henneberg]], [[Benedikt Schack|Schack]], and [[Franz Xaver Gerl|Gerl]]. In 2004, it gave the first UK staged performance of [[Antonio Salieri|Salieri]]'s ''[[Falstaff_(Salieri)|Falstaff]]'', and in July 2007 staged the UK premi\u00e8re of [[Georg Benda]]'s ''[[Romeo und Julie|Romeo and Juliet]]''. It also performed the [[Mozart]] arrangement of [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]]'s ''[[Acis and Galatea (Handel)|Acis and Galatea]]''. In 2008 it presented ''[[Leonora (opera)|Leonora]]'' by [[Ferdinando Paer]], based on the same story as ''[[Fidelio]]'', and in 2009 ''[[Le pescatrici|Le Pescatrici]]'' (''The Fisherwomen'') by [[Haydn]]. In 2010, it presented the UK premi\u00e8re of [[Marcos Portugal]]'s ''The Marriage of Figaro'' (1799), and [[Alfred (Arne opera)|''The Masque of King Alfred'']] and [[The Judgement of Paris (opera)|''The Judgment of Paris'']] by [[Thomas Arne]]. In 2011, it presented more performances of the Arne double-bill; ''Il parnaso confuso'' by [[Gluck]]; ''[[The Italian Girl in London]]'' (''L'italiana in Londra'') by [[Domenico Cimarosa|Cimarosa]], first performed in 1778; and [[The Choice of Hercules (Handel)|''The Choice of Hercules'']] by [[Handel]]. In 2012, it presented a revival of Marcos Portugal's ''The Marriage of Figaro'' and new productions of ''[[L'amant jaloux]] (The Jealous Lover)'' by [[Andr\u00e9 Gr\u00e9try]] (1778) and ''[[Blaise le savetier]] (Blaise the Cobbler)'' (1759) by [[Fran\u00e7ois-Andr\u00e9 Danican Philidor]]. In 2013, it presented a new production of Mozart\u2019s first comic opera, ''[[La finta semplice]]'' (1769), in a new English translation, ''Pride and Pretence''. In 2014, it revisited ''[[La finta semplice]]'' and Gluck's ''[[Il Parnaso confuso|Il parnaso confuso]]'', as well as presenting ''[https://www.bamptonopera.org/operadetail.htm?opera=32 Orfeo]'' by [[Ferdinando Bertoni]]. In 2015, Bampton Classical Opera performed Salieri's ''[[La grotta di Trofonio|Trofonio's Cave]]''. In 2016, it staged a double bill called the ''Divine Comedies'' featuring Arne's ''[[The Judgement of Paris (opera)|The Judgement of Paris]]'' and Gluck's ''Philemon and Baucis'' - an English translation of part two of ''[[Le feste d'Apollo]]''. In 2017, it presented ''[https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2017/salieris-school-jealousy-review-st-johns-smith-square/ The School of Jealousy]'' by Salieri. In 2018, it presented Isouard's ''[[Cendrillon (Isouard)|Cinderella]]'' and Menotti's ''[[Amahl and the Night Visitors]]''. In 2019, it performed ''[https://https://bamptonopera.org/brideandgloom.htm Bride and Gloom (Gli sposi malcontenti)]'' by [[Stephen Storace]] in an English translation by [[Brian Trowell]].<ref>[https://www.bamptonopera.org/archive.htm  Bampton Classical Opera, Past Productions]</ref>\n[[Image:Stephen Storace's Gli sposi malcontenti, 2019 performance (as 'Bride & Gloom') by Bampton Classical Opera.png|thumb|300px|Stephen Storace's ''Gli sposi malcontenti'', 2019 performance (as ''Bride & Gloom'')]]\n\nThe company's patrons are [[Bonaventura Bottone]], [[Brian Kay]], Sir [[Roger Norrington]], [[Andrew Parrott]], Sir [[David Pountney]], Sir [[Curtis Price]] and [[Jean Rigby]].<ref>[https://www.bamptonopera.org/index.htm  Bampton Classical Opera]</ref> Dame [[Felicity Lott]], the late Sir [[Charles Mackerras]] and the late Sir [[Philip Ledger]] were also patrons, as was the Rt Hon [[David Cameron]], in whose former [[Witney (UK Parliament constituency)|Witney]] constituency Bampton lies.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n*Jones, Roger, Review of Thomas Arne's ''Masque of King Alfred'' and ''The Judgment of Paris'', [http://www.musicweb-international.com/sandh/2010/Jul-Dec10/arne0711.htm ''MusicWeb International''] 7 November 2010 (accessed 29 January 2011)\n*Church, Michael, Review of Benda's ''Romeo and Juliet'' at Bampton Classical Opera, [http://arts.independent.co.uk/music/reviews/article2980490.ece ''The Independent''] 20 September 2007 (accessed 24 September 2007)\n*Tanner, Michael, Review of ''Acis and Galatea'', [http://www.spectator.co.uk/arts-and-culture/featured/31052/part_3/laughter-unbecoming.thtml ''Spectator''] 24 May 2007 (accessed 29 January 2011)\n*Porter, Andrew, Review of [[Vicente Mart\u00edn y Soler|Mart\u00edn y Soler]]'s ''La scuola dei maritati'' at Bampton Classical Opera, [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/incomingFeeds/article617035.ece ''The Times''] 18 August 2006 (accessed 22 June 2007)\n*Thicknesse, Robert, Review of [[Giovanni Paisiello|Paisiello]]'s ''The Barber of Seville'' at Bampton Classical Opera, [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/article546151.ece ''The Times''] 21 July 2005 (accessed 22 June 2007)\n*Thicknesse, Robert, Review of French double bill, Bampton Opera, [http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/leisure/music_and_books/music/9838988.French_double_bill__Bampton_Opera__The_Deanery_Gardens__Bampton ''Oxford Times''] 26 July 2012 (accessed 23 August 2012)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bamptonopera.org Bampton Classical Opera website]\n[[Category:British opera companies]]\n[[Category:Opera in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Opera in London]]\n[[Category:Opera festivals]]\n[[Category:Classical music festivals in England]]\n[[Category:Music festivals in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Winstonsmith99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Improving reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bampton_Classical_Opera"}
